Token ‘t46’ can only be produced by the single–rule non-terminal NT1:

 NT1 → 't46'

Whenever NT1 is used in a derivation it yields exactly one token and nothing follows it, because its only alternative rule is

 NT1 → NT21 NT64 ,

and neither NT21 nor NT64 (nor anything that can be reached from them) can generate ‘t46’.  
Thus, in any sentence generated by the grammar, the occurrence of ‘t46’ must be the very last token of the whole sentence.

In the given string ‘t46’ appears in position 28, while tokens 29–39 ( ‘t140 t4 t12 t117 t7 t90 t106 t124 t9 t197 t90’ ) still follow it.  
Hence the string cannot be produced by the grammar.
